Message:
Hi Guys
.
How do i make the "freegames" module effective???
.
.
"""Ant, simple animation demo.

Exercises

1. Wrap ant around screen boundaries.
2. Make the ant leave a trail.
3. Change the ant color based on position.
   Hint: colormode(255); color(0, 100, 200)

"""

from random import *
from turtle import *
from freegames import vector

ant = vector(0, 0)
aim = vector(2, 0)

def wrap(value):
    "Wrap value around -200 and 200."
    return value  # TODO

def draw():
    "Move ant and draw screen."
    ant.move(aim)
    ant.x = wrap(ant.x)
    ant.y = wrap(ant.y)

    aim.move(random() - 0.5)
    aim.rotate(random() * 10 - 5)

    clear()
    goto(ant.x, ant.y)
    dot(4)

    if running:
        ontimer(draw, 100)

setup(420, 420, 370, 0)
hideturtle()
tracer(False)
up()
running = True
draw()
done()
#PYTHON

Message:
Spending a little idle time I stumbled across Jean-Fran√ßois Pugets Christmas Gift (https://www.ibm.com/developerworks/community/blogs/jfp/entry/my_christmas_gift ) Jupyter notebook from a few years ago which uses numba to speed up the calculation of mandelbrot fractals. 

I thought I would test to see if the Just In Time compiler was really making that much of a difference so copied the 2 functions were it is used and renamed then & removed the @jit decorators from the copies then compared the times with %timeit - the results were impressive:

80 iterations with @jit: 3.1 s ¬± 665 ms per loop (mean ¬± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1 loop each)
80 iterations without: 27.7 s ¬± 1.66 s per loop (mean ¬± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1 loop each)
800 iterations with @jit: 28.1 s ¬± 3.28 s per loop (mean ¬± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1 loop each) 
800 iterations without: 206s ¬± 12.1 s per loop (mean ¬± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1 loop each)

I have to say that I am impressed - of course the numba @jit decorator will have the most impact on processor bound, tight, numeric loops but there are a quite lot of those about.

Message:
Kivy
Innovative user interfaces made easy.
Kivy is an open source, cross-platform
Python framework for the development of applications that make use of innovative, multi-touch user interfaces. The aim is to allow for quick and easy interaction design and rapid prototyping whilst making your code reusable and deployable.
Kivy is written in Python and Cython , based on OpenGL ES 2, supports various input devices and has an extensive widget library. With the same codebase, you can target Windows, OS X, Linux, Android and iOS. All Kivy widgets are built with multitouch support.
Kivy is MIT licensed, actively developed by a great community and is supported by many projects managed by the Kivy Organization.

#Solving a quadratic equation
Import cmath
a = float(input('Enter a:'))
b = float(input('Enter b:'))
c = float(input('Enter c:'))
d = (b**2)-(4*a*c)
X1 = (-b-cmath.sqrt(d))/(2*a)

print('the solution is (0) and (1)'.format(X1,X2))

Message:
I share a example of Matrix Multiplication for beginners
a = input("number of first matrix's rows?")
a = int(a)
b = input("number of second matrix's rows?")
b = int(b)
print("first matrix's elements?")
x = [[int(x_temp) for x_temp in input().strip().split(' ')] for y_temp in range(a)]
print("second matrix's elements?")
y = [[int(x_temp) for x_temp in input().strip().split(' ')] for y_temp in range(b)]
z = [[0 for i in range(len(y[0]))] for j in range(a)]
for i in range(a):
for j in range(len(y[0])):
for k in range(b):
z[i][j]=x[i][k]*y[k][j]+z[i][j]
print("result: ",z)

Message:
Here's a fun challenge:

Implement a program that produces the see and say sequence.

The see and say sequence is as follows:
Each item is how you say the previous item when counting the kinds of digits from left to right. The sequence is primed with 1.

So, the first item is 1. There's one 1.

That means the second item is 11.

see_and_say = [1, 11]

The second item is two 1s. So the the item is 21.

see_and_say = [1, 11, 21]

The third item has one 2 followed by one one. So the fourth item is 1211.

see_and_say = [1, 11, 21, 1211]

And so on and so forth forever.

Bonus points:
*Make it lazy
*Implement slicing
*Have an optional argument to prime the sequence with a number other than one
*Have an optional keyword argument to make the numbers read from right to left rather than left to right

I literally just came up with this, so I don't have my own answer yet. I'll post it once I work on it.

Message:
Hi all, i wanted the data from an xml file if  value tag having 'S:' in the text so i will get the value text ,filter code and  sccpAddress from 'sender' tag, i have made a python scripts i,e :

import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
tree = ET.parse('rawfile.xml')
root = tree.getroot()

for child in root:
    order = child.find('sender')
    for i in child.iter('filter'):
        for j in child.iter('diagnostic'):
            for k in j.iter('data'):

#!/usr/bin/env 
from socket import *
from time import ctime

HOST = ''
PORT = 21567
BUFSIZ = 1024
ADDR = (HOST, PORT)
tcpSerSock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM)
tcpSerSock.bind(ADDR)
tcpSerSock.listen(5) 

while True:
    print 'waiting for connection...'
    tcpCliSock, addr = tcpSerSock.accept()
    print '...connected from:', addr
        while True:
             data = tcpCliSock.recv(BUFSIZ)
             if not data:
                 break
             tcpCliSock.send('[%s] %s' % (ctime(), data))
        tcpCliSock.close()
tcpSerSock.close()

This is code in Flask 
----------------------------
#!/usr/bin/python
#--coding: utf-8 --
import pymysql
import simplejson as json
from flask import Flask, render_template, request
app = Flask(__name__, template_folder='template')

db = pymysql.connect(host='localhost' ,user='root' ,password='Mart' ,db='flaskpy' ,charset='utf8' ,use_unicode=True)
cursor = db.cursor()

@app.route("/json")
def createjson():
    sql = "select*from test"
    cursor.execute(sql)
    results = cursor.fetchall()
    try:
        list_of_dict = []
        for row in results:
            data = {}
            data['id'] = row[0]
            data['name'] = row[1]
            data['lname'] = row[2]
            data['age'] = row[3]
            list_of_dict.append(data)
            return render_template("uploadjson.html")

        with open('list_of_dict.json', 'w') as cfile:
            json.dump(list_of_dict, cfile, ensure_ascii=False)
        with open('list_of_dict.json') as data_file:
            data_loaded = json.load(data_file)
        print(list_of_dict == data_loaded)

    except:
        print("error")
    db.close()
     

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)

Message:
#Emulating_Switch_in_python

#code

def switch(opr, x, y):
    return {
    '+': lambda: x+y,
    '-': lambda: x-y,
    '*': lambda: x*y,
    '/': lambda: x/y
    }.get(opr, lambda: None)()

opr = input("Type (|+|-|*|/|) >>> ")
x = input("Num_1 >>> ")
x = int(x)
y = input("Num_2 >>> ")
y = int(y)

print(switch(opr, x, y))

Message:
PLEASE USE PYTHON! (Please use beginner methods if possible please) :( :(

DNA Sequencing:

The term DNA sequencing refers to methods for determining the order of the nucleotide bases, adenine, thymine, cytosine, and guanine in a molecule of DNA. The standard representation of the bases is to use their first letters, ATCG, so that DNA is represented as a string using only those four characters. However, DNA strings are millions of bases (characters) long.
Substring matching is the process of determining whether a shorter string (the substring) is contained within a longer string. Substring matching plays important roles in the reconstruction of an unknown DNA string from pieces and in searching for interesting
substrings within a known DNA string.
Python provides a find(substring, start, end) string method that returns the lowest index (integer) where the substring is found in the index range start ‚â§ index <
end. The start and end arguments are optional, but for this exercise we will make them required. If the substring is not found, -1 is returned.

(a) Without using the find string method, write a function that behaves exactly like the find string method. As your function is not a string method, the string to search must be an argument‚Äîlet‚Äôs make it the first one. The resulting format of your function will be:
            find(some_string, substring, start, end)
For example, if some_string is ‚ÄòACGTCGA‚Äô and ‚Äòsubstring‚Äô is ‚ÄòCG‚Äô, your find function should return 1.

(b) Biology researchers frequently want to find all the locations where a substring is found, not simply the first one. Write a function named multi_find(some_string, substring, start, end) that, instead of returning one integer index, returns a string that contains zero or more indices separated by commas. In this case, the string will contain digits representing the integer indices. If the substring is not found, an empty string is returned. You may use the find method that you wrote earlier.
For example, if some_string is ‚ÄòACGTCGA‚Äô and ‚Äòsubstring‚Äô is ‚ÄòCG‚Äô, your find function should return ‚Äò1,4‚Äô.

Message:
Hello all,

Thanks for having me here. However, I'm a proper novice and beginner in Programming and I'm starting with python so I need assistance with solutions to some basic problems in python. Please find below the questions:

1. Write a program in python that accepts a number between 0-9 as argument. This function should then return the word representation of the number.

2. Using Python, write a function that accepts a String argument and prints the String converted to uppercase.

3. What will be the output of this code snippet?print ‚ÄúI love programming‚Äù [1:-5]

4.Write a program in python that accepts a number between 0-9 as argument. This function should then return the word representation of the number.
Your answer

5. Write a function fizzbuzz , this function should take a number as an argument. The function should return ‚Äúfizz‚Äù if the number is divisible by 3, but should return ‚Äúbuzz‚Äù if divisible by 5. If divisible by both 3 and 5, it should return ‚Äúfizzbuzz‚Äù.

6. Create a class RECTANGLE (in Python), this class should define a constructor that initializes two properties: length and breadth. This class should also have the following methods:- setLength(length) ------->This can be used to set the length property of the object. getLength() ------> This can be used to retrieve the length of the object. setBreadth(breadth) ----- This can be used to set the breadth property of the object. getBreadth() -------> This can be used to get the breadth property of the object. calculateArea() -----> This will calculate and return the area of the rectangle object. printArea() ------> This will calculate and print the area of the rectangle object

Please @everyone...in case you're seeing or reading this. Please I need your answers to these problems and I'll be very glad at the earliest response I get

Message:
Here's a good Python trick:

If you have a function that can take keyword arguments, but you don't know which ones you'll want to pass it in advance, you can build a dictionary of them like so:

kwargs = {}
kwargs['foo'] = 5
kwargs['bar'] = "All your base are belong to us!"
kwargs['baz'] = 3.14159

and then pass it to the function like this:

keyword_function(**kwargs)

and it's the same as if you'd called

keyword_function(foo=5, bar="All your base are belong to us!", baz=3.14159)

Message:
So I'm gonna share now my hangman game.
The rar file is composed of two files which are the "hangman.pyw" and the "py.png", program will not run unless "py.png" is present in the same directory where the "hangman.pyw" is placed. The script ends with ".pyw" so that no console will pop-up whenever the script will run. I used tkinter and turtle in writing this project. The python version used is 3.6.2. The OS used is windows 10. This is an object-oriented program that consists of one class named "HangMan" and this class contains 31 methods. I didn't compile it to an executable so that you can edit things in it. If it doesn't run in your system, comment here something about the problem.

Message:
For complete beginners who want to learn PYTHON, Before learning python, have an idea about what are all the things you can do using Python. Here are the few common cool things listed.

->Web Development : You can develop a website with a backend supporting REST api using python frameworks such as DJANGO/FLASK.
->Game Development : You can develop a video game using a python module PYGAME.
->Computer Vision : You can do interesting thongs such as face detection, color detection using OPENCV with python.
->Web Scarping : If you want to get data from a website but the website doesn't have an API to expose data, you can use python modules REQUESTS, SCRAPY, BEAUTIFULSOUP to support web scraping.
->Machine Learning : You can do cool things such as predicting stocks, finger print identification, spam detection etc.,using machine learning. Python has modules SCIKIT-LEARN, THEANO, TENSORFLOW to support it. currently Deep Learning has all the hype and TENSORFLOW has support for Deep Learning.
->GUI Development : To develop a cross-platform desktop application, python has modules TKINTER, PYQT to support it.
->Robotics : Raspberry Pi can be used as a brain to the robot to perform various actions and to react to the environment and the coding on a Raspberry Pi can be done using Python.
->Data Analysis : Data whenever obtained either online or offline would not be properly formatted with various issues such as missing values etc., This data can be cleaned(formatted in a proper sequence) using python module PANDAS. and to visualize the data, python module MATPLOTLIB can be used.
->Browser Automation : Cool things such as opening a browser and posting a facebook status can be done using SELENIUM with python.

and the list goes on but above are the very common things in the real world.

Hope this would be helpful for you guys!
Author: Yoganand Chowdary

Message:
hi guys, I tried to write some sort of contact manager ,  ill post my code, ill appreciate your thoughts on that , thanks a lol, by the way I start to learn python alone and just for about 4 weeks so I am super beginner :D 

users = []
import winsound
import time

def menu():
    time.sleep (.50)
    winsound.Beep(1000,500)
    print("||||||||||||| Contacts Manager v1 by: K-N |||||||||||")
    print("")
    print("--- Options------------------------------------------")
    print ("Add new contact  1)")
    #print ("Save/Exit        2)")
    print ("Show raw data    2)")
    #print ("Load database    4)")
    print ("Lookup           3)")
    print ("exit             4)")
    
    
def options():
    menu()
    option = int(input("choose: "))
    if option == 1:
        addnew()
    #elif option == 2:
        save()
    elif option == 2:
        show()
    #elif option == 4:
        #load()
    elif option ==3:
        lookup()
    elif option ==4:
        q()
    else:
        print("try again")
        options()            

def save():
    savefile = open ('data.txt','a')
    savefile.write("\n".join (str(i) for i in users ))
    savefile.close()
    #options()
    
def startupload():
    loadin = open('data.txt', 'r')
    for line in loadin.readlines():
        for element in line[0:-1].split('\n'):
            users.append(element)
            winsound.Beep(3500,50)
            print("Element loaded")
            time.sleep(0.01)
    open ('data.txt', 'w').close
    options()
    
def addnew():
    print ("Add new contact")
    print ("---------------")

    name = input ("name: ")
    phone = input ("phone: ")
    email = input ("email: ")
    address = input("address: ")
    users.append ([name, phone, email, address])
    
    addmore = input ("Add more? ")
    if addmore == "yes":
        addnew()
    elif addmore == "no":
        options()
    
def show():
    print ("----------------------------------------------------------------")
    for i in users:
        print("\n",i)
        winsound.Beep(3500,50)
    print ("----------------------------------------------------------------")
    print ("")
    done = input("press a key: ")
    options()

def lookup():
        search = input ("search: ")
        for i in users:
            for j in i:
                if search in i or search in j:
                    print (i * 1)
                    input ("press a key to release")
                    options()
                    
                
def q():
    done = input("exit? ")
    if done == "yes":
        save()
        time.sleep(1)
        
        print("terminating")
        time.sleep(0.25)
        winsound.Beep(700,100)
        print("|||")
        time.sleep(0.25)
        winsound.Beep(500,100)
        print("   |||")
        time.sleep(0.25)
        winsound.Beep(300,100)
        print("      |||")
        time.sleep(1)
        exit()
    else:
        options()

try:
    startupload()
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("No data file found !! ")
    print("restarting program")
    time.sleep(1)
    winsound.Beep(1000,500)
    options()

Message:
Hi need some help in the below code.I now have pysftp working but it required me to disable loading hostkeys using pysftp.Cnopts(). The file it is looking for does not exist on windows machines and hence why it throws the warning (/.ssh/known_hosts). The program functions as intended but is there a way to silence the warning message or create/use some other host file to allow pysftp to function normally?

this is the code : where i have to include the following two statements in the code:
cnopts = pysftp.CnOpts()
cnopts.hostkeys = None

here is the code:
import pysftp
import sys
import os
import smtplib
from datetime import datetime
from email.mime.text import MIMEText

def main():
    dir = []
    files = []
    try:
        srv = pysftp.Connection(host="xxxx", username="xxxx", password="xxxx" )
    except Exception as e:
        send_email(u'Connection error: ' + e.message)
    
    with srv.cd():
        srv.chdir("file location")  
        files = srv.listdir()
    dt = datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d')
    files = [f for f in files if 'Shape_147_BATCHECP_{}_0'.format(dt) in f]
    if len(files) != 1:
        send_email('Error: No file found on FTP path. Please check whether file is posted for today')
        return

    _filename = "filelocation"+files[0]
    srv.get(_filename)

    # Closes the connection
    srv.close()

    # rename the file
    new_filename = 'location'
    # new_filename = 'Location'
    try:
        os.remove(new_filename)
    except Exception as e:
        send_email(u'Move error: ' + e.message)
    
    os.rename(files[0], new_filename)

def send_email(message):
    ''' Send email to support alias'''
    msg = MIMEText(message)

    sender = 'shaan.tableau@gmail.com'
    support_alias = 'shaan.tableau@gmail.com'
    msg['Subject'] = 'Test file '
    msg['From'] = sender
    msg['To'] = support_alias

    # Send the message via our own SMTP server, but don't include the
    # envelope header.
    s = smtplib.SMTP('smtp.net')
    s.sendmail(sender, [support_alias], msg.as_string())
    s.quit()    

if __name__ == '__main__':
  main()

Message:
Does anyone else ever have moments where you just want to throw your computer into an incinerator and go live in the woods? I'm having one now.

I'm finally getting a Qt-based GUI put together for the server monitoring tool I've been working on for a while now. I wanted to add a button that opens a new terminal window right to an SSH session - which should be pretty straightforward I thought. Well, (insert image of Donald Trump) wrooooooong. Unlike literally every terminal emulator on literally every other Unix-based OS from the 21st century, Terminal.app doesn't provide any way to open it with an initial command. So I had to learn AppleScript (which I had zero interest in ever laying eyes on, much less using) just so I could write a tiny three-line helper script to accomplish what should have been a ridiculously easy task. 

I thought getting it to work on Windows was gonna be the only pain in my ass, but I guess not.

Hi Everyone,
Actually any object can uploaded into s3 and automatically stored into Database This is my code and it will not getting an error but didn't store url links into Databse

import sys, os, Image
import boto3
from boto.s3.connection import S3Connection
import MySQLdb

db = MySQLdb.connect(host= "localhost",user="root",passwd="root",
                     db="urlfromS3")
cursor = db.cursor()

client = boto3.client('s3')
AWS_KEY = '*****'
AWS_SECRET = '****'
aws_connection = S3Connection(AWS_KEY, AWS_SECRET)
bucket = aws_connection.get_bucket('vvek')
i=0
for img in bucket.get_all_keys():
    ext = [".JPG", ".jpg", ".png", ".PNG"]
    if img.name.endswith(tuple(ext)) and img.size > 1*1024:
        i = i+1
        imgID = i
        iname = img.name
        url = img.generate_url()
        print url
        query = 'INSERT INTO URL (url) VALUES (%s)'
        cursor.execute(query, [url])
        db.commit()
db.close()
